@Node "Assembler Options" "pro.guide/Assembler Options"

Assembler Options
.................

@{b}Include Directories@{ub}
     Include search pathes tell the assembler where to look for files
     to be included by the @{b}INCLUDE@{ub} or @{b}INCBIN@{ub} directives, or their
     synonyms.  A new path can be added by either selecting the @{b}Add@{ub}
     gadget that opens a file requester to select the directory, or its
     name can be typed into the string-gadget.  You do not have to
     enclose the path name in double or single quotes if it contains
     one or more whitespaces.  ProOpts encloses automatically all
     entries with double quotes if needed.

     When the settings are stored, these include directories are all
     written as arguments of the @{b}INCDIR@{ub} directive to the configuration
     file.  See @{"INCDIR" Link "pro.guide/INCDIR"}.

@{b}Custom Lines@{ub}
     When a configuration file is loaded at startup or via the @{b}Open...@{ub}
     menu item, all lines that could not be recognized by ProOpts are
     put in this list.  See @{"ProOpts Directives Summary" Link "ProOpts Directives Summary"}, for a list of
     all valid directives.

     The custom lines list can also be used to add directives to the
     configuration file that are not supported by ProOpts.  You may
     even put complete macro definitions into the list.  Awkward, but
     it works.

@{b}No XPK Support@{ub}
     This check-gadget controls the XPK support.  XPK support is
     disabled when the gadget is set.  See @{"OPT NOXPK" Link "pro.guide/OPT XPK"}.

@{b}Assembly Priority@{ub}
     Using the integer-gadget you have the possibility to set the task
     priority of the assembler while running (see @{"ASMPRI" Link "pro.guide/ASMPRI"}).

     Note that ProOpts does not check the range of the entered value to
     its validity.  The range of the priority are the integers from
     -128 to 127.  The CLI and the most other tasks have a priority of
     0, and it is suggested that you do not set the priority higher
     than 10.  A priority higher than zero means that the assembler
     will not be slowed down as much by other tasks.  Setting the
     priority lower than 0 will prevent ProAsm from slowing down other
     programs with normal priority.

@{b}Symbol Search@{ub}
     With this cycle-gadget you can select an appropriate symbol search
     algorithm for your source codes.  You can choose between @{b}Standard@{ub}
     (default), @{b}ESS1@{ub}, @{b}ESS2@{ub}, and @{b}ESS3@{ub}.  See @{"OPT ESS1" Link "pro.guide/OPT ESS1"}, for more details.


@EndNode

@Node "Code Options" "pro.guide/Code Options"

Code Options
............

@{b}CPU@{ub}
     This cycle-gadget specifies the processor to be programmed for.
     See @{"Processor Type" Link "Processor Type"}, for more information.

     Note that the cycle-gadget entry @{b}Any@{ub} represents the @{b}MCRELAX@{ub}
     directive.

@{b}FPU@{ub}
     This cycle-gadget allows you to specify the floating-point
     coprocessor you want to program for to allow its instruction set.
     See @{"MC68881" Link "pro.guide/MC68000"}, for more details.

     Note that the MC68040 and MC68060 processor have built-in FPU.
     Their FPU instruction sets are automatically allowed when the
     specific processor is selected (see the @{b}CPU@{ub} gadget above).

@{b}MMU@{ub}
     This cycle-gadget only toggles between @{b}None@{ub}, for no MMU, and
     @{b}MC68851@{ub}.  See @{"MC68851" Link "pro.guide/MC68000"}, for more details.

     Note that the MC68030, MC68040, and MC68060 MMU instruction set
     will automatically be enabled when the specific CPU has been
     selected (see the @{b}CPU@{ub} gadget above).

@{b}Case@{ub}
     With this cycle-gadget you can toggle between case @{b}sensitive@{ub} and
     @{b}unsensitive@{ub} symbols.  See @{"OPT C" Link "pro.guide/OPT C"}, for more information.

@{b}Symbol Significance@{ub}
     Specifying a value using the integer-gadget makes the first part
     of symbol case sensitive or unsensitive, according to @{b}Case@{ub} (see
     above).  See @{"OPT C" Link "pro.guide/OPT C"}, for more information.

     Note that ProOpts does not perform a range check on the entered
     value.  Valid values must be from 0 to 256, where 0 turns the
     symbol significance off.

@{b}Underscore for Local Labels@{ub}
     If this gadget is selected, the underscore (@{b}_@{ub}) rather than the dot
     (@{b}.@{ub}) is used to introduce a local label (see @{"OPT U" Link "pro.guide/OPT U"}).

@{b}Warn not Supervisor Instructions@{ub}
     This check-gadget allows you to enable or disable all warnings on
     supervisor-only opcodes.  The warnings are disabled when the
     gadget is selected.  See @{"SUPER" Link "pro.guide/SUPER"}, for more details.

@{b}Warn not Read-Modify-Write Instr.@{ub}
     You can suppress all warnings for read/modify/write instructions
     by selecting this check-gadget.  See @{"READMODWRITE" Link "pro.guide/READMODWRITE"}.

@{b}Ensure PC-Relative Code@{ub}
     Selecting this check-gadget forces the assembler to report a
     @{b}relocation not allowed@{ub} error on any instructions that require
     relocation.  See @{"OPT P" Link "pro.guide/OPT P"}, for more information.

@{b}Immediate Data Check@{ub}
     All absolute addresses will be checked for missing pound signs (@{b}#@{ub}),
     when this check-gadget is selected (see @{"OPT I" Link "pro.guide/OPT I"}).

@{b}Automatic PC-Relative@{ub}
     In selected state this gadget forces the assembler to use the
     PC-relative addressing mode where possible instead of the absolute
     long addressing mode.  See @{"OPT AUTOPC" Link "pro.guide/Optimization"}, for more information.

@{b}Control software-supported instructions@{ub}
     These two cycle-gadgets allow you to control the use of
     software-supported instructions.

     The first cycle-gadget enables or disables the software-supported
     floating-point instructions of either the MC68040, the MC68060, or
     both processors.  The second gadget controls only the use of the
     MC68060 software-supported integer instructions.

     See @{"OPT FPSP40" Link "pro.guide/Processor Options"},and @{"OPT SP60" Link "pro.guide/Processor Options"}, for more detailed information.

@{b}Bit Number@{ub}
     Using this cycle-gadget you can decide whether a warning, no
     warning, or an error should be reported if ProAsm encounters a bit
     number that is not in bounds.  See @{"OPT CHKBIT" Link "pro.guide/OPT CHKBIT"}.

@{b}(Syntax) Model@{ub}
     This gadget can be used to determine whether the assembler should
     accept the new syntax model, the old one, or both.  See @{"NEWSYNTAX" Link "pro.guide/Syntax Options"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Default Options" "pro.guide/Default Options"

Default Options
...............

    In the default options window you have the possibility to define
the default behaviour of ProAsm.  Refer to @{"Assembly Options" Link "Assembly Options"}, for more
details on these and possible settings.  ProOpts uses the @{b}DEFAULT@{ub}
directive for all these cycle-gadgets when saved to the configuration
file.  See @{"DEFAULT" Link "pro.guide/DEFAULT"}, for information about this directive and its
arguments.  The cycle-gadgets let you specify the @{i}mode@{ui} arguments of the
@{b}DEFAULT@{ub} directive.

@{b}Default Branch Size@{ub}
     Corresponds to @{b}DEFAULT _BRANCH,@{i}mode@{ui}@{ub}.

@{b}Default Base Displacement@{ub}
     Corresponds to @{b}DEFAULT _BASEDISP,@{i}mode@{ui}@{ub}.

@{b}Default Outer Displacement@{ub}
     Corresponds to @{b}DEFAULT _OUTERDISP,@{i}mode@{ui}@{ub}.

@{b}Default PC Displacement@{ub}
     Corresponds to @{b}DEFAULT _PCBASEDISP,@{i}mode@{ui}@{ub}.

@{b}Default Address Displacement@{ub}
     Corresponds to @{b}DEFAULT _ADRBASEDISP,@{i}mode@{ui}@{ub}.

@{b}Linker References@{ub}
     Corresponds to @{b}DEFAULT _LINKREF,@{i}mode@{ui}@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "Miscellaneous Options" "pro.guide/Miscellaneous Options"
@Next "Optimization Options"
@Prev "Default Options"
@Toc "Using ProOpts"

Miscellaneous Options
.....................

@{b}Suppress All Warnings@{ub}
     This check-gadget lets you suppress all warning messages (see
     @{"OPT NOWARN" Link "pro.guide/OPT NOWARN"}).

@{b}Timing Information@{ub}
     Using this cycle-gadget you can select the way the assembler
     should report timing information and their quantity.  See @{"VERBOSE" Link "pro.guide/VERBOSE"}.

@{b}Suppress All Errors@{ub}
     This check-gadget lets you suppress all error messages (see @{"OPT E" Link "pro.guide/OPT E"}).

@{b}Error Failat Level@{ub}
     The value in the integer-gadget specifies the maximum number of
     errors to be reported before aborting assembly.  A value of zero
     sets the limit to unlimited number of errors.  See @{"FAILAT" Link "pro.guide/FAILAT"}.

@{b}Enable Escape Strings@{ub}
     This check-gadget controls the allowance of escape sequences
     withing strings.  If it is selected, escape sequences are allowed.
     See @{"ESCAPESTR" Link "pro.guide/ESCAPESTR"}.

@{b}Enable Type Checking@{ub}
     Select this check-gadget to enable type checking.  Refer to
     @{"Type Checking" Link "pro.guide/OPT T"}, for more detailed information.

@{b}Do Not Report Odd Addresses@{ub}
     If you select this check-gadget, all misalignment and odd access
     checks are disabled and no errors will be issued (see @{"ODDOK" Link "pro.guide/ODDOK"}).

@{b}Report Odd PC Relative Displacements@{ub}
     By selecting this check-gadget additional misalignment and odd
     access checks are performed by the assembler.  See @{"ODD2ERROR" Link "pro.guide/ODD2ERROR"}.

@{b}Report Multiple Includes@{ub}
     This check-gadget can be used to tell the assembler to report
     multiple includes, instead of ignoring them.  See @{"OPT Y" Link "pro.guide/OPT Y"}.

@{b}Show Filenames@{ub}
     Select this check-gadget to let the assembler report the name of
     all loaded include files (see @{"OPT F" Link "pro.guide/OPT F"}).


@EndNode

@Node "Optimization Options" "pro.guide/Optimization Options"

Optimization Options
....................

    The optimization options are spread over two windows.  The
descriptions of the individual options can be found by either the @{b}OPT O@{ub}
option (see @{"OPT O" Link "pro.guide/Optimization"}), or the @{b}OPT Q@{ub} (see @{"OPT Q" Link "pro.guide/Optimization"}), unless otherwise noted.
In the following tables you find only the options the gadgets
correspond to.

@{b}No Optimization Warnings@{ub}
     This gadget disables all warnings that are generated by
     optimizations.  See @{"OPT OW" Link "pro.guide/OPT OW"}.

@{b}Multipass optimization@{ub}
     If this check-gadget is selected, multipass optimization is
     enabled (see @{"MULTIPASS" Link "pro.guide/Optimization"}).

@{b}Use proasmoptim.library@{ub}
     This gadget enables the use of the optimizer library (see
     @{"OPT OPTIMLIB" Link "pro.guide/Optimization"}).

@{b}Backward Branches@{ub}
     Corresponds to the @{b}OPT O1+@{ub} option.

@{b}Warn Forward Branches@{ub}
     Corresponds to the @{b}OPT O6+@{ub} option.

@{b}Zero Offsets@{ub}
     Corresponds to the @{b}OPT O2+@{ub} option.

@{b}Absolute Addressing@{ub}
     Corresponds to the @{b}OPT O3+@{ub} option.

@{b}MOVE.L to Quick@{ub}
     Corresponds to the @{b}OPT O4+@{ub} option.

@{b}ADD/SUB to Quick@{ub}
     Corresponds to the @{b}OPT O5+@{ub} option.

@{b}CMPI/CMPA.x #0 to TST@{ub}
     Corresponds to the @{b}OPT O9+@{ub} option.

@{b}Short Base Displacement@{ub}
     Corresponds to the @{b}OPT O13+@{ub} option.

@{b}Short Outer Displacement@{ub}
     Corresponds to the @{b}OPT O14+@{ub} option.

@{b}Short Immediate Data@{ub}
     Corresponds to the @{b}OPT O8+@{ub} option.

@{b}CLR.L Dn to MOVEQ #0,Dn@{ub}
     Corresponds to the @{b}OPT Q1+@{ub} option.

@{b}ASL/ROXL.x #1,Dn to ADD/ADDX.x@{ub}
     Corresponds to the @{b}OPT Q2+@{ub} option.

@{b}Next Page@{ub}
     By pressing this gadget, you change to the next optimization page.

@{b}PC-Relative Addressing@{ub}
     Corresponds to the @{b}OPT O7+@{ub} option.

@{b}MOVE.B #-1,<EA> to ST.B <EA>@{ub}
     Corresponds to the @{b}OPT Q11+@{ub} option.

@{b}Skip ADDA/SUBA #0,An@{ub}
     Corresponds to the @{b}OPT Q4+@{ub} option.

@{b}MOVEQ #0,An to SUBA.L An,An@{ub}
     Corresponds to the @{b}OPT Q3+@{ub} option.

@{b}MOVE.L #x,Dn to MOVEQ #y,Dn & NOT.x Dn@{ub}
     Corresponds to the @{b}OPT Q5+@{ub} option.

@{b}MOVE.L #x,Dn to MOVEQ #y,Dn & SUBQ.L #y,Dn@{ub}
     Corresponds to the @{b}OPT Q7+@{ub} option.

@{b}MOVE.L #x,Dn to MOVEQ #y,Dn & SWAP Dn@{ub}
     Corresponds to the @{b}OPT Q8+@{ub} option.

@{b}MOVE.L #x,Dn to MOVEQ #y,Dn & ADD.B Dn,Dn@{ub}
     Corresponds to the @{b}OPT Q9+@{ub} option.

@{b}EOR(I).x #-1,<EA> to NOT.x <EA>@{ub}
     Corresponds to the @{b}OPT Q12+@{ub} option.


